<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday. Unless Elon Musk does something =
weird I guess.</em></p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" =
cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Incora</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a schematic description=
 of how modern distressed-debt investing works[1]:</p><ol style=3D"list-sty=
le-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">A company borrows $1 billion, in a syndicated loan or a bo=
nd issue, from a bunch of different investors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">As is customary, the loan agreement or bond indenture says =E2=
=80=9Cthis agreement may be amended by a majority of the investors.=E2=80=
=9D[2]</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Time passes and the company=
 runs into some trouble.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The compa=
ny goes out to 51% of the investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0holders of $510 million =
of the bond or loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0and says: =E2=80=9CPsst. We will pay you=
 back 110=C2=A0cents on the dollar =E2=80=94=C2=A0$561 million total =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0if you agree to let us stiff the other guys.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So the 51% holders vote to amend the agreement=
 to say =E2=80=9Cthese holders will get 110 cents on the dollar, and the ot=
her holders will get zero.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">The other 49% are really mad=C2=A0and surprised.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">The amendment works, 51% of the holders make a nice profit=
, 49% of the holders lose all their money, and the company pockets the extr=
a $439 million.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now of course I am ki=
dding, and you can=E2=80=99t actually do this. But it would be cool if you =
could (for the company, and the 51% creditors). And it is a good model to k=
eep in mind, because modern distressed investing often works by getting <em=
>as close as possible=C2=A0</em>to this.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e reason this schematic version doesn=E2=80=99t work is that the bond inden=
ture or loan agreement will say =E2=80=9Cthis agreement may be amended by a=
 majority of the investors,=E2=80=9D but it will include a lot of exception=
s that either require a supermajority or can=E2=80=99t be amended at all.[3=
] Most notably, you can=E2=80=99t amend the <em>principal</em>; you can=E2=
=80=99t get a majority of bondholders to vote that some (or all) of the bon=
ds will get paid back $0.[4] So my little schematic description can=E2=80=
=99t work.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you can amend=C2=A0<em>other=
=C2=A0</em>things about the loan or bond, and the game is to amend it to ma=
ke things unpleasant ways for the 49% while making things more pleasant for=
 the 51%. You take value from the 49% lenders, you give some of it to the 5=
1% as a payoff for approving the deal, and you keep the rest of it for the =
company.=C2=A0Much of the action in recent years has been about priming and=
 lien stripping:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40=
px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A company issues =
a secured loan or bond, giving creditors a lien on all of the company=E2=80=
=99s assets. The loan has security provisions, like =E2=80=9Cthis loan is s=
ecured by a first lien on all of the assets,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe canno=
t issue any debt with a higher-priority claim on our assets.=E2=80=9D</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The loan or bond says =E2=80=9Cthis ag=
reement may be amended by a majority of investors, except that we can=E2=80=
=99t amend fundamental provisions like how much we pay back and when, etc.=
=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The list of exceptions d=
oes not include the liens, or the covenant against issuing higher-priority =
debt.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Time passes and the company =
runs into some trouble.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The compan=
y goes to the 51% and says =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99ll give you an extra-sup=
er-top-priority lien on all of our assets in exchange for taking away the l=
iens from the other guys.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>The 51% vote to amend the agreement to allow new higher-priority bonds, ex=
change their old bonds into the new higher-priority bonds, and on the way o=
ut vote to amend the old bonds to release their liens and no longer be secu=
red by any assets.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The other 49% n=
ow own unsecured bonds and are real sad.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">This is not as exciting as my first, extremely schematic version, mainl=
y because in this version the company still has to pay back the 49%. The de=
bt doesn=E2=80=99t go away; it just becomes riskier. In practice, this trad=
e only happens when the company is in serious distress: Stripping liens on =
the 49% and giving priority to the 51% is only valuable to the 51% if the c=
ompany might not have enough money to pay everyone. And it only makes sense=
 for the company if it gets something in return from the 51%. Generally thi=
s means new money: For instance, the 51% roll their $510 million of old deb=
t, plus $250 million of new cash, into $760 million of new super-priority b=
onds, giving the company a bit more money to operate in exchange for the hi=
gher security. (The 51% might also extend maturities, reduce interest rates=
, etc., to give the company more breathing room, though new money is usuall=
y a key ask.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some variations on the theme.=
 First of all, in my basic description, I say that the company goes to 51% =
of the investors and offers to bribe them in exchange for hosing the 49%. A=
nd in fact that is a thing that happens, because the company is often owned=
 by a private equity sponsor who loves extracting value from creditors. Pri=
vate equity sponsors are always thinking about clever new ways to take mone=
y from creditors and give it to themselves.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>But it could also happen the other way: If you own some bonds, and you can=
 get your friends together until you own 51%, why not go to the company (or=
 its sponsor) and ask for a little payoff? Getting 110 cents on the dollar =
is better than 100, and certainly better than zero, and if you can offer th=
e company a way to extract money from other bondholders, keep some for itse=
lf, and give some to you, why not do it?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Es=
pecially because everyone else is doing it! It is much better for you to re=
ceive a small bribe to zero other creditors than it is for you to be zeroed=
 because other creditors received a small bribe. And so in practice in some=
 distressed-debt situations there is a horrible race in which two different=
 groups of creditors get together to try to (1) get a majority of the debt =
and (2) be the first to offer the company a trade that advantages their gro=
up and hoses the other group of creditors.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Another variation: Let=E2=80=99s say you can get, say, 40% of the cre=
ditors together to agree to do the thing you want. That=E2=80=99s not a maj=
ority. Does that mean you can=E2=80=99t do it? Nah! Here=E2=80=99s the trad=
e:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16=
px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Get 40%.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Have the company=C2=A0<em>issue some more=C2=A0</em>of t=
he debt=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Caccordion=E2=80=9D the term loan, reopen the=
 bond deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0to the 40% holders, until they have 51%.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Vote on the amendment you want, etc.</li><=
/ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This does not always work =E2=80=94=C2=A0s=
ometimes the agreement will not permit the company to issue more debt, and =
if you don=E2=80=99t have a majority yet you can=E2=80=99t amend=C2=A0it[5]=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but sometimes it does.=C2=A0If you can get close to a major=
ity, you can issue yourself the rest of the way there. Or, similarly, if yo=
u need a supermajority to do what you want to do, you can issue more bonds =
until you have the votes you need.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway h=
ere=E2=80=99s the latest <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/27290711.284600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjItMDQtMDUvc2lsdmVyLXBvaW50LXBpbWNvLWNvb2stdXAtY3JlZGl0LXRyYWRlLXRoYXQ=
taGFzLXJpdmFscy1mdW1pbmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQwNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNDA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
j1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf2506d69" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> ghastly distres=
sed-debt deal</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week, s=
truggling aerospace supplier Incora secured a financial lifeline from a gro=
up of investors including Silver Point Capital and Pacific Investment Manag=
ement Co. that pushed rival creditors down the repayment line, aided by unu=
sually aggressive moves from its private-equity sponsor Platinum Equity.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The transaction -- known as priming -- is eli=
citing uproar from the creditors left behind. It=E2=80=99s also sparking fr=
esh fears in the industry that investors are ramping up a costly fight amon=
gst themselves to put money to work in an evaporated $200 billion pool of d=
istressed debt.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wesco Aircraft Holdings Inc=
., which operates under the name Incora, forged a deal with both investment=
 firms that will give it $250 million of fresh cash and swap bonds due in 2=
024 for longer-dated maturities.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =
new securities will be backed by collateral that was previously pledged to =
other creditors, meaning those outside the Silver Point-led group -- includ=
ing Golden Gate Capital, JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co.=E2=80=99s asset managemen=
t arm and funds managed by BlackRock Inc. -- will be left worse off in any =
future restructuring.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both Silver Point and=
 Pimco negotiated a deal with the firm and Platinum directly, which ultimat=
ely diluted the claims of other creditors on Incora=E2=80=99s assets, accor=
ding to people with knowledge of the matter who asked not to be identified =
discussing private discussions. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">P=
latinum owned some of Incora=E2=80=99s unsecured debt and rolled up its hol=
dings, a move considered unusual and aggressive to industry observers, the =
people said. The transaction transformed a slug of secured and unsecured de=
bt into new longer-dated secured debt that ranked ahead of existing obligat=
ions and reduced protections on those older debts. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Some holders of Incora=E2=80=99s 9% secured bonds due 202=
6, fearing how their positions would fare, banded together to try to block =
the deal, the people said. When it appeared the bondholder group was large =
enough to stop the transaction, Incora issued more 2026 securities -- dilut=
ing the other creditors=E2=80=99 stake. The move then handed Pimco and Silv=
er Point enough votes to allow Incora to issue the new, higher-ranking obli=
gations, the people said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Inco=
ra had some secured bonds outstanding, secured by liens on the company=E2=
=80=99s assets. Those bonds have a provision saying that holders of two-thi=
rds of the bonds can vote to amend them to release the liens on the collate=
ral.[6] The Pimco and Silver Point group owned a lot of the bonds, but not =
two-thirds. But the bond indenture also allowed Incora to issue a bit more =
debt, so it did, to Pimco and Silver Point, giving them the two-thirds they=
 needed. Once they had the votes, they voted to (1) allow issuance of new, =
super-priority debt and (2) to=C2=A0<em>take away=C2=A0</em>the collateral =
from the existing bond. Then they exchanged their (now unsecured) bond into=
 the new, super-priority bonds. They also let Platinum exchange some of its=
 unsecured debt =E2=80=94=C2=A0which had ranked below the old secured bonds=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0into new secured bonds, letting Platinum jump ahead of the =
other (formerly) secured creditors. Here is how=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27290711.284600/aHR0cHM6Ly9wZXRpdGlvbi5z=
dWJzdGFjay5jb20vcC9pbmNvcmFkZWFs/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8745502b" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>the Petition newsletter describes the mechanics</a>:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Step One: Issue incremental basket capacity to Silve=
r Point and PIMCO =E2=80=A6 dilute the minority non-participating lenders a=
nd hand Silver Point and PIMCO the steering wheel =E2=80=A6 mutually agree =
to amend basket capacity under the indenture to issue a meaningful amount o=
f new debt =E2=80=A6 use that new power to viciously strip liens from the o=
ther noteholders =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Step Two: Permit=
 Silver Point and PIMCO to exchange their pre-existing secured notes =E2=80=
=A6 plus newly issued secured notes =E2=80=A6 into new superpriority secure=
d 26s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0dusting the Akin cohort [<em>i.e., the other group of =
bondholders</em>] in the processssssssssssss.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Step Three: Let Platinum have some fun toooooo. Uptier their holdings in=
 unsecured 27s into ~$475mm of new 1.25 lien notes due in =E2=80=9822 (most=
ly PIK) and =E2=80=9823 (higher cash pay, but also PIK) AT PAR (lol) =E2=80=
=A6 prime the minority secured lenders(!!!!!!!!) =E2=80=A6and dust the stub=
 piece of unsecured bondholders too LOLOL</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Is this allowed? I don=E2=80=99t know, it is at least arguably =
allowed; Incora and Pimco and Silver Point think it=E2=80=99s allowed. The =
other side seems pretty upset. The 9% bonds due 2026, which have about $882=
 million outstanding and were trading at about 103 cents on the dollar on M=
arch 23,[7]=C2=A0are at about 69 cents today. This deal extracted about $30=
0 million of value from those bonds=C2=A0and redistributed it among Incora,=
 its sponsors and the bondholders who won.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Broadly speaking you can=E2=80=99t do stuff like this in the stock market. =
Broadly speaking, companies have fiduciary duties to their shareholders, an=
d have some baseline obligation=C2=A0to treat them all equally. This is not=
 always binding in every way, but it is a good general starting point; you =
can=E2=80=99t get 51% of shareholders to vote themselves a big dividend at =
the expense of the other 49%.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the =
debt market, this is not the baseline assumption: The company is not a fidu=
ciary for its lenders; it owes them only what the contract says it does.=C2=
=A0If the contract is not airtight, the company and 51% of its lenders can =
gang up to abuse the other 49%. The contract probably=C2=A0<em>isn=E2=80=99=
t=C2=A0</em>airtight, in part because it is hard to write an airtight 100-p=
age contract, in part because lenders in bull markets are not always stickl=
ers about negotiating airtight covenants, and in part because it=C2=A0<em>s=
houldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>be; there=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>be some flex=
ibility for the company to renegotiate its debt to respond to, for instance=
, a business downturn during a pandemic. You could write the contract to sa=
y =E2=80=9Cwhatever we do, we will always treat all lenders equally,=E2=80=
=9D[8]=C2=A0but again that limits the company=E2=80=99s flexibility =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it is pleasant, for the company, to be able to play lenders off ag=
ainst each other =E2=80=94=C2=A0and is not always the rule.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/27290711.284600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW5jb3JhLmNvbS9uZXdzLWZ=
lYXR1cmVzL25ld3MtZmVhdHVyZXMtZGV0YWlsLz9pZD1pbmNvcmEtY29tcGxldGVzLWNvbXByZW=
hlbnNpdmUtcmVjYXBpdGFsaXphdGlvbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB10175cfc" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>how Incora described the deal</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The recapitalization, which includes an immediate liquidity infusion o=
f $250 million, was supported by majorities across all of the company's fun=
ded debt including bondholders and bank lenders.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">"This is a resounding vote of confidence from our financing partners =
and a great day for Incora and its employees, customers, vendors and busine=
ss partners," said David Coleal, Incora's chief executive officer. =C2=A0"T=
his transaction provides a combination of fresh liquidity, maturity relief =
and debt service reduction, allowing Incora the financial stability to cont=
inue delivering innovative, first-in-class service to our existing customer=
s, and to seize new business opportunities as the defense industry signals =
increased growth and the commercial aerospace industry rebounds."</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That sounds so much nicer! Maybe it=E2=
=80=99s right? The basic way distressed investing works now is that a compa=
ny that is having a hard time can extract value from some of its lenders, g=
ive it to its other lenders, and stay afloat a while longer. That=E2=80=99s=
